# Firebase Security Rules — Mandatory Sync

Security rules in `firestore.rules` and `database.rules.json` are the **last line of defense** against unauthorized data access. They MUST always reflect the actual data access patterns in the codebase.

## Rule Files

| File | Database | Deployed via |
|------|----------|-------------|
| `firestore.rules` | Firestore | `firebase deploy --only firestore:rules` |
| `database.rules.json` | Realtime Database | `firebase deploy --only database` |

Both files are referenced in `firebase.json` and deployed automatically in CI (`deploy.yml`).

## When to Update Rules

You MUST update security rules when ANY of these changes happen:

| Change | Action |
|--------|--------|
| New Firestore collection or subcollection | Add `match` block with appropriate read/write rules |
| New RTDB node | Add node entry in `database.rules.json` |
| Service function changes who reads/writes | Verify existing rules still allow the operation |
| New Cloud Function that writes to Firestore/RTDB | Ensure client rules deny what should be server-only (`allow write: if false`) |
| Auth flow changes (new sign-in method, roles) | Update `request.auth` conditions in affected rules |
| Schema file (`.schema.json`) added or modified | Verify rules cover the path documented in the schema |

## Rule Design Principles

### Deny by Default

```
// Firestore — catch-all at the bottom
match /{document=**} { allow read, write: if false; }

// RTDB — root-level deny
{ "rules": { ".read": false, ".write": false, ... } }
```

Every new path MUST have explicit rules. The catch-all denies anything not explicitly allowed.

### Minimum Privilege

| Pattern | Meaning |
|---------|---------|
| `request.auth.uid == uid` | Only the document owner |
| `request.auth != null` | Any authenticated user |
| `if false` | Cloud Functions only (Admin SDK bypasses rules) |

Prefer owner-only access. Use `auth != null` only when cross-user reads are architecturally necessary (e.g., students reading teacher channels).

### Separate Read/Write

Always split permissions — NEVER use blanket `allow read, write` unless ownership is verified:

```
allow read: if request.auth != null;
allow create: if request.auth != null;
allow update, delete: if request.auth != null && request.auth.uid == uid;
```

## Current Architecture

### Firestore

| Path | Read | Write | Notes |
|------|------|-------|-------|
| `users/{uid}` | Owner | Owner | Teacher profiles |
| `users/{uid}/channels/{id}` | Authenticated | Owner | Students discover channels via enrollment |
| `users/{uid}/students/{idNum}` | Authenticated | Create: authenticated; Update/Delete: owner | Students join, teachers manage |
| `students/{idNum}` | Authenticated | `false` (Cloud Functions only) | Student profiles — written by `studentRegister` |
| `students/{idNum}/workspaces/{teacherUid}` | Authenticated | Teacher (`teacherUid`) | Workspace mirror synced by core-web |

### Realtime Database

| Node | Read | Write | Notes |
|------|------|-------|-------|
| `studentCredentials/{idNum}` | `false` | `false` | Server-only — Cloud Functions use Admin SDK |
| `codes/{code}` | Authenticated | Authenticated | Invite code lookup + generation |
| `userCodes/{uid}` | Owner | Owner | Teacher's invite code |

## Rules Testing — `@firebase/rules-unit-testing`

Tests live in `tests/rules/` and run against the Firebase emulators:

| File | Tests |
|------|-------|
| `tests/rules/firestore.test.ts` | Every Firestore `match` block — read, write, create, update, delete per role |
| `tests/rules/database.test.ts` | Every RTDB node — read, write per role |
| `tests/rules/vitest.config.ts` | Vitest config — `node` environment, 30s timeout |

Run with: `pnpm run test:rules` (starts emulators automatically via `firebase emulators:exec`).

### When to Update Tests

| Change | Required test update |
|--------|---------------------|
| New `match` block in `firestore.rules` | Add `describe` block in `firestore.test.ts` covering read/write for owner, authenticated, unauthenticated |
| New node in `database.rules.json` | Add `describe` block in `database.test.ts` covering read/write for owner, authenticated, unauthenticated |
| Permission change on existing rule | Update existing test assertions to match the new behavior |
| Rule removed | Remove corresponding test block |

### Test Structure

Each `describe` block MUST cover at minimum:

- **Allow cases**: every role that SHOULD have access (owner, authenticated, etc.)
- **Deny cases**: every role that MUST NOT have access (non-owner, unauthenticated)
- **Operation granularity**: separate tests for `read`, `create`, `update`, `delete` when rules differ by operation

A rule without a test is not considered deployed. A test without a corresponding rule is dead code.

## Rules

- NEVER deploy an app that reads/writes a new DB path without updating rules first
- NEVER use `allow read, write: if true` — even temporarily
- NEVER remove the catch-all deny block at the bottom of `firestore.rules`
- Security rules are deployed BEFORE hosting and functions in CI — rules must be in place when new code goes live
- When adding a new `.schema.json`, verify a corresponding rule exists in `firestore.rules` or `database.rules.json`
- Review `firestore.rules` and `database.rules.json` in every PR that touches `services/` or `apps/functions/`
- EVERY rule change MUST include a corresponding test update in `tests/rules/` — run `pnpm run test:rules` to verify
- NEVER merge a PR that adds/modifies rules without passing `test:rules`
